  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3392691375" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3392691375" />
    <a title="Ozymandias" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22223147-ozymandias"><img alt="Ozymandias" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1373892974p2/22223147.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3392691375?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ozymandias" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ozymandias" href="/user/show/22223147-ozymandias">Ozymandias</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8147859-battle-cry-of-freedom">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22223147-ozymandias?shelf=modern-history">modern-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22223147-ozymandias?shelf=american">american</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22223147-ozymandias?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3392691375" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6497930951517436916">This is the best overview I’ve ever read on the American Civil War. It’s been widely hailed as a classic, and rightly so. I’ve read multi-volume books (see the Foote trilogy) that couldn’t manage to get all the nuance this book managed in one. What makes it so good? It covers <i>everything!</i> From the war’s origins through espionage through naval war through tactics and strategy to political structure to racial prejudice to imperialism to economics to... etc. <br/><br/>One part of what makes the book readable </span>
  <span id="freeText6497930951517436916" style="display:none">This is the best overview I’ve ever read on the American Civil War. It’s been widely hailed as a classic, and rightly so. I’ve read multi-volume books (see the Foote trilogy) that couldn’t manage to get all the nuance this book managed in one. What makes it so good? It covers <i>everything!</i> From the war’s origins through espionage through naval war through tactics and strategy to political structure to racial prejudice to imperialism to economics to... etc. <br /><br />One part of what makes the book readable instead of just insightful is the way that it’s organize. The book has good use of chapters on several thematic topics arranged where it’s chronologically appropriate. For example, the chapter on fiscal policies appears amid discussion of military events in early 1862 when both sides were coming to consensuses on the issues. And the discussion of naval warfare fits into the discussion of late 1861 when the blockade runners and the Confederacy’s campaign to get British intervention was most active. The fact that the chapter then continues on into the Monitor/Merrimack fight of 1862 and indeed summarizes the situation of the navy for the rest of the war doesn’t really get ahead of the main narrative because it’s an isolated subject. Vital, but isolated.<br /><br />I really appreciated the division and focus on how much attention to give each area. It shows the balance of the war pretty well. It’s not just a string of Southern triumphs until Grant takes charge and brings the whole force of the industrialized North into play. The war hung on a tightrope the whole time. Even the generalization that the South was mainly dominant until Gettysburg reflects an unjustly eastern perspective. The West was really the decisive theater of the war. That’s where the Confederacy was split and Sherman led his army through Georgia to the sea and enveloped the eastern theater from behind. But what shines out the strongest was how important Grant’s (and Lincoln’s) strategy was to success: attack on all fronts simultaneously so the outnumbered South couldn’t move around reinforcements. Grand strategy was what won the war.<br /><br />Probably the best thing about this book though is how effectively it demolishes the whole “Lost Cause” narrative that dominates so many of the popular and therefore accessible accounts: that the war was initiated by a few radicals (mainly abolitionists who wrongly opposed white supremacy) and was fought over the question of State’s Rights. What State’s Rights? They never say. And McPherson is blunt in calling them out on it. The right they were defending was slavery, and they wanted to defend it (ironically) by intruding on Northern state’s rights by gaining federal protections for slaveowners in all territories. In short, the cause of the war was that the North wanted to prevent the expansion of slavery and the South would accept nothing less than its enforcement across <i>all</i> states in the union. Including the free states of the north. Inasmuch as there was a second most important issue it was white supremacy. A poor Southerner would never be able to afford his own slaves, but at least he was superior to a nigger. And yes, that’s exactly how they put it. Alexander Stephens (VP of the Confederacy) gave a whole speech about the superior moral and economic virtue of slavery: it kept the childish, unmanageable blacks under control and working for the benefit of white men who thereby gained the leisure to pursue a worthy culture.<br /><br />This book isn’t revisionist history, it’s a reversion from the accounts put forth by decades of revisionist historians (Stephens himself changed his argument after the war) who sought to give the Lost Cause some luster while justifying the continued oppression of their African-American population. And Northern historians were equally complicit in promoting the cause of white supremacy, even if it meant ignoring quite literally everything said by any Southern politician before and during the war.<br /><br />The obvious implications of the “Lost Cause” narrative are plain, but there are a lot of subsidiary ones that are equally distorted. I had never, for example, questioned that the South was the real underdog in the war. The North had all the industry, railroads, and manpower so naturally they could overpower the South through force of numbers. But that’s a product of the South’s comforting effort to explain away defeat as a noble cause beyond their control. The North’s advantages were obvious, yet they took time to mobilize and weren’t necessarily decisive. And the South had advantages too. A substantial number of talented generals, interior lines, and a monopoly on cotton that made them potentially attractive to European traders.<br /><br />The North’s objective was also a lot harder. The South merely had to keep an army in the field and threaten Union forces. The North had to invade hostile territory and fill it with garrisons to keep the population in line and protect vital infrastructure. Something that would go a long way to reducing their superiority in numbers. If you look to Europe, Southern victory was considered inevitable well into 1863. Why? Because they knew how exceedingly difficult it was to hold such a large territory against the will of its inhabitants. Looking at the closest comparison, the American Revolution, it’s clear that subduing a dispersed population who didn’t want to be subdued was no easy feat. And had things gone only slightly differently that’s the “inevitable” outcome we would have been taught.<br /><br />McPherson’s emphasis at all points is on contingency. The North’s industrial and manpower advantages ultimately prevailed because they were successful in battle. Their unified strategy across all fronts managed to capitalize on their advantages while exploiting real weaknesses in the South. This didn’t derive from any universal principle of superiority of resources. In fact, even when adopting this strategy they could have failed. Even in 1864, a delay in Northern success could easily have left McClellan not Lincoln as president. And that could easily have meant a Southern victory (certainly it would have meant the continuation of slavery and likely a further war down the road).<br /><br />There’s a lot here I don’t have room to unpack. The book is, after all, very long and filled with facts. That it’s eminently readable as well is a true achievement. This should be the starting point for anyone interested in the Civil War.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6497930951517436916" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

