  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3570908971" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3570908971" />
    <a title="CoachJim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53002487-coachjim"><img alt="CoachJim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609602625p2/53002487.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3570908971?book_show_action=true">Oct 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CoachJim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CoachJim" href="/user/show/53002487-coachjim">CoachJim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780195038637" href="/book/show/77369.Battle_Cry_of_Freedom">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53002487-coachjim?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3570908971" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14673057392840744585">Battle Cry of Freedom: The Civil War Era<br/>by James M. McPherson<br/><br/>The late C. Vann Woodward in the Editor’s Introduction to this volume notes how unique this book is in that it is a one volume history of the Civil War. This becomes remarkable in that this is the longest of the ten <i>Oxford History of the United States</i> series, and also covers the shortest period of any of the volumes.<br/><br/>In this volume the author covers all the aspects of life and war. He deals with the politics, the culture, the economics,</span>
  <span id="freeText14673057392840744585" style="display:none">Battle Cry of Freedom: The Civil War Era<br />by James M. McPherson<br /><br />The late C. Vann Woodward in the Editor’s Introduction to this volume notes how unique this book is in that it is a one volume history of the Civil War. This becomes remarkable in that this is the longest of the ten <i>Oxford History of the United States</i> series, and also covers the shortest period of any of the volumes.<br /><br />In this volume the author covers all the aspects of life and war. He deals with the politics, the culture, the economics, diplomacy by both the North and South, the varying goals of the war by both sides, the treatment of the POWs, and, of course, the military activities. For some one interested in an overall survey of the period this is an excellent source. For me this was the best of the 4 volumes I have read this year from this series.<br /><br />The first 300 pages or so cover the <i>antebellum</i> period and based on the reading I have done this year of that period it is a good summary. The gradual divisions of the country are explored. This becomes a division between Jeffersons Republicanism and the new capitalist system practiced in the North. There is a the belief that Jeffersonian agrarianism was culturally superior to the Capitalism of the North. The South’s defense and rationalization of slavery is described. The South tries to compare the life of slaves on their plantations with the poor workers in Northern factories. This division becomes one of separate political parties, but eventually becomes a divide between the sections of the country. Here the leading question becomes the status of slavery in the new territories. <br /><br />For someone interested in the battles of the Civil War this is probably not the book for you. Although all of the major battles are mentioned there is not much detail regarding the military aspects of the battles. For me once you have read about the thousands of corpses lying in the fields there is no reason for more battle descriptions. The horrific casualties were a result of military tactics not keeping up with modern weaponry. One of the reoccurring issues that is raised is the incompetence of the various military leaders — McClellan, Meade for the North, and Bragg, Pemberton and Hood for the South. Here it is hard to not blame McClellan and Meade for the horrific results of these battles. They had opportunities to bring the War to an end, but their lack of boldness missed those chances.<br /><br />The industrialization of the North and the greater population gave the North an advantage that over time made a victory by the South unlikely. In discussing the failure of economy of the South it is quoted:<br /><br /><blockquote> <b>classical economists considered free labor more efficient than slave labor because the free worker is stimulated by the fear of want and the desire for betterment. A slave, wrote [Adam] Smith, “can have no other interest but to eat as much, and to labor as little as possible.”</b></blockquote><br /><br /><br />Lincoln’s original reason for fighting the Civil War was to preserve the union, but as the military difficulties increased he began toying with the idea of an Emancipation Proclamation. His reasons had more to do with turning the tide of the war instead of freeing the slaves. But the Emancipation Proclamation unleashed a wave of racism in both the North and the South. The roots of racism in this country run deep, but they grew deeper during this period. In the South the Confederacy needed to keep the poor whites and the non-slaveowners loyal to the cause. They did this by convincing the poor whites that even though they were poor being white still made them superior to the slaves. In the North the idea of freed slaves competing for the jobs was used to scare the working class. This racism took on even worse forms when fears were spread of racial amalgamation. The 1864 Presidential election found the Democratic party using racism as its major platform.<br /><br />As the difficulties grew for the South attempts to raise more men for the army faced its own States Rights problem. This led to internal conflicts which weakened the Confederacy. The individual Confederate states did not feel they were bound to the obey the policies of the Confederacy. Another interesting note here was that the one political party in the South allowed several members of their Congress to run as independents. This led to so many varied ideas that no unanimity was found. In the North the two party situation instilled some party discipline.<br /><br />There is a chapter entitled “Fire in the Rear” which describes the civilian woes during the War. However, I found this chapter to be especially cluttered with statistics which detracted from the reading.<br /><br />The Epilogue to this book was the most interesting to me. Here the question is discussed as to Why The South Lost. He mentions the “Lost Cause” mentality and the worship of Robert E. Lee. The author presents several reasons given by the South for the cause of their loss and then refutes each of them. Here he mentions the “Rich man’s war and the poor man’s fight”; An attitude in both the North and the South. He discusses the ability of the Republicans in the North to close ranks on the Democratic party’s obstruction. His main point is that many historians have ignored the “dimension of contingency”. There were numerous critical points during the war where things could have gone differently and drastically changed the course of the War. For example, the fall of Atlanta in the Fall of 1864 probably ensured Lincoln’s reelection.<br /><br />His most interesting observation here was the amount of change this War brought to the Country. The more centralized National government vastly expanded its powers at the expense of the States. This paralleled a shift of political power from the South to the North. The change in the Country during the span of 4 years led many to feel like they were now living in a different country.<br /><br />The challenges ahead that are described in many books about the Reconstruction await. I hope I can find some as interesting as this one.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14673057392840744585" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


